[White spot viral disease (WSVD) has caused high mortalities and severe damage to the shrimp culture industry in China, Thailand, Japan, Taiwan, Indonesia and India. The virus was 1st detected in Taiwan in 1992, and then it spread to Japan and almost all Asian countries. The 1st diagnosed case of WSVD in the Americas occurred in 1995 in a South Texas shrimp farm, and it was suggested that the most probable route for its introduction was through an Asian imported frozen-bait shrimp commodity. In February 1999, the virus caused massive mortalities in some farms in Ecuador, while the most recent outbreak in an area with free status according to OIE criteria, occurred in Brazil in 2005.

Acutely affected shrimps are reported to show a rapid reduction in food consumption, become lethargic and have a loose cuticle with white spots (hence, the name "white spot" disease) of 0.5 to 2.0 mm in diameter, which are more apparent on the inside surface of the carapace. The white spots represent abnormal deposits of calcium salts by the cuticular epidermis.

For a picture of a shrimp with white spot syndrome go to https://shrimpdiseases.wordpress.com/wssv/.

Portions of this comment were extracted from http://www.vetres.org/articles/vetres/full_html/2010/06/v09431/v09431.html.- Mod.PMB

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4615506,6.]
